                      <span>2005-02-16</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>After working with the author for more than 2 years, it's hard to understand how someone who studies other companies' best practices can manage his own company so poorly. He's the last person I'd take advice from on how to measure performance and run a company. He insribed my copy of this book with the words, "Let the masters be our mentors." Well, I definitely never learned anything from this "mentor." I'd place this book in the bottom quartile of my library.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Excellent Book For the Beginning Benchmarker</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>7</span>
                      /
                      <span>8</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2000-03-01</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Bogan and English do a great job of introducing benchmarking, give great examples, and follow up with a nice set of "practice problems".  They provide success stories and pitfalls to be avoided.  Most importantly  they give an excellent planning chapter for the company just beginning  benchmarking.  Great introduction to the topic.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Must reading for anyone implementing benchmarks</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>10</span>
                      /
                      <span>10</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>1999-09-16</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>As a responsible management consultant, virtually every one of my engagements involves measurement and benchmarking in one form or another.  This is one of several books I turn to time and again to assist me in  ensuring that my clients' initiatives are (1) meeting expectations (2)  providing competitive advantage and (3) delivering customer satisfaction.  If you have any questions, please feel free to email me -  adamleft@webspan.net.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Adopt a we-can-learn-from-anyone culture or else</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>7</span>
                      /
                      <span>8</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>1997-01-09</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Bogan and English have created  a blueprint for creating this we-can-learn-from-anyone culture of benchmarking that is easy to read and use.  They give literally hundreds of examples and suggestions for how to select benchmarking targets, organize for rapid learning, and implement these strategies.   Learning by borrowing from the best and adapting their approaches makes sense.  Buy this book before your competitors do</span>
                  
              
